==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Christianize
<hw>Chris"tian*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Christianized</conjf>
<pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Christianizing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>christianiser</ets>, L. <ets>christianizare</ets>, fr. Gr.
<?/.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make Christian; to convert to
Christianity; <as>as, to <ex>Christianize</ex> pagans</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To imbue with or adapt to Christian
principles.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Christianized</qex> philosophers.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Christianize</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Christianize
<hw>Chris"tian*ize</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To adopt the character or
belief of a Christian; to become Christian.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The pagans began to <qex>Christianize</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Latham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Christianlike</ent>⟦br⟧
